Wait, the original 404.js uses `router.push('/')` with a button. In App Router, `<Link>` is fine for navigation. But if they want to keep the programmatic navigation feel, I could use a Client Component. Actually, for simplicity and to keep it as a Server Component, I'll just use `<Link href="/">`.

Hmm, but the original actually uses a `<button>` with `router.push`. Let me think...

The 404 page in App Router is a Server Component by default. I can use a `Link` component. But if I want to match the exact behavior of the original, I'd need either:
1. A `<Link>` component (which is fine for navigation)
2. A client component with `useRouter`

I'll go with `<Link>` since it's simpler and functionally equivalent for "go to home page."

### 4. `app/error.tsx`

```tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>Something went wrong!</h1>
      <p>{error.message || 'An error occurred on client'}</p>
      <button onClick={reset}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Wait, the original `_error.js` handles both client and server errors with `getInitialProps`. In App Router, the pattern is different:
- `error.tsx` catches errors in client-rendered portions
- For server errors, it just shows the error boundary

The original has: "A {statusCode} error occurred on server" vs "An error occurred on client" and handles 404 separately.

Since we already have a `not-found.tsx`, the error page just needs to handle unexpected errors. But the original was more nuanced. Let me think...

Actually, in App Router:
- `not-found.tsx` handles 404s (both `notFound()` calls and unmatched routes)
- `error.tsx` handles 500-level errors

The `error.tsx` is a Client Component. It gets `error` and `reset` props. We don't get a statusCode directly in error.tsx, but we can check `error.digest` or just show a generic error message.

Let me look at Next.js docs pattern for error.tsx:

```tsx
'use client';

export default function Error({
  error,
  reset,
}: {
  error: Error & { digest?: string };
  reset: () => void;
}) {
  return (
    <div className="error-page">
      <h1>Something went wrong!</h1>
      <button onClick={() => reset()}>Try again</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

I'll keep it reasonably close to the original spirit but adapted to App Router patterns.

### 5. `app/blog/page.tsx`

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
  userId: number;
}

export const metadata: Metadata = {
  title: 'All Blog Posts',
  description: 'Browse all blog posts',
};

export const revalidate = 60;

export default async function BlogPage() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts');

  if (!res.ok) throw new Error('Failed to fetch posts');

  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>All Blog Posts</h1>
      <div className="posts-grid">
        {posts.map((post) => (
          <div key={post.id} className="post-card">
            <h2>
              <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>{post.title}</Link>
            </h2>
            <p>{post.body.substring(0, 100)}...</p>
            <Link href={`/blog/${post.id}`}>Read More</Link>
          </div>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Wait, the original blog/index.js used a button with `router.push('/blog/${post.id}')` for "Read More". Again, I'll use `<Link>` instead.

For ISR equivalent, I export `revalidate = 60` at the page level if using fetch-level revalidation isn't enough. Actually, with this fetch pattern, we should use:

```ts
const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts', {
  next: { revalidate: 60 },
});
```

Or just export `revalidate` at the page level. Both work. Let me use the page-level `revalidate` since it's cleaner for the whole page.

### 6. `app/blog/[id]/page.tsx`

This needs both `generateStaticParams` (replacing getStaticPaths) and the page component (replacing getStaticProps).

```tsx
import Link from 'next/link';
import type { Metadata } from 'next';

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  body: string;
  userId: number;
}

interface Comment {
  id: number;
  name: string;
  body: string;
  email: string;
  postId: number;
}

interface Props {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>;
}

export async function generateStaticParams() {
  const res = await fetch('https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts?_limit=10');
  const posts: Post[] = await res.json();

  return posts.map((post) => ({
    id: String(post.id),
  }));
}

export const dynamicParams = true; // equivalent to fallback: 'blocking'

export async function generateMetadata({ params }: Props): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params;
  const res = await fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`);

  if (!res.ok) return { title: 'Post Not Found' };

  const post: Post = await res.json();

  return {
    title: post.title,
    description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    openGraph: {
      title: post.title,
      description: post.body.substring(0, 160),
    },
  };
}

export default async function BlogPostPage({ params }: Props) {
  const { id } = await params;

  const [postRes, commentsRes] = await Promise.all([
    fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}`, {
      next: { revalidate: 300 },
    }),
    fetch(`https://jsonplaceholder.typicode.com/posts/${id}/comments`, {
      next: { revalidate: 300 },
    }),
  ]);

  if (!postRes.ok) {
    // notFound() would work here but we need to import it
    return <div>Post not found</div>;
  }

  const post: Post = await postRes.json();
  const comments: Comment[] = await commentsRes.json();

  return (
    <article>
      <Link href="/blog">← Back</Link>
      <h1>{post.title}</h1>
      <p>{post.body}</p>

      <section className="comments">
        <h2>Comments ({comments.length})</h2>
        {comments.map((comment) => (
          <div key={comment.id} className="comment">
            <h3>{comment.name}</h3>
            <p>{comment.body}</p>
            <p>
              <em>By {comment.email}</em>
            </p>
          </div>
        ))}
      </section>
    </article>
  );
}
```

Wait, the original used `router.back()` for the back button. Since this is a Server Component, I'll use `<Link>` with `/blog`. Actually I could also make just the "Back" part a Client Component, but `<Link>` is simpler and functionally equivalent.

Also, the original had `isFallback` handling. In App Router with `dynamicParams: true`, the `generateStaticParams` pre-renders ids 1-10, and any other id will be generated on first request (the equivalent of `fallback: 'blocking'`). So there's no explicit `isFallback` check needed.

### 7. `app/providers.tsx`

```tsx
'use client';

import { createContext, useContext, useState, ReactNode } from 'react';

interface AppContextType {
  theme: string;
  setTheme: (theme: string) => void;
}

const AppContext = createContext<AppContextType | null>(null);

export function useAppContext() {
  const context = useContext(AppContext);
  if (!context) {
    throw new Error('useAppContext must be used within AppProvider');
  }
  return context;
}

export default function Providers({ children }: { children: ReactNode }) {
  const [theme, setTheme] = useState('light');

  return (
    <AppContext.Provider value={{ theme, setTheme }}>
      {children}
    </AppContext.Provider>
  );
}
```

### 8. API Route Handlers

**`app/api/posts/route.ts`:**
```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
}

const posts: Post[] = [
  { id: 1, title: 'First Post', content: 'This is the first post.' },
  { id: 2, title: 'Second Post', content: 'This is the second post.' },
];

export async function GET() {
  return NextResponse.json(posts);
}

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json();
  const { title, content } = body;

  if (!title || !content) {
    return NextResponse.json(
      { error: 'Title and content are required' },
      { status: 400 }
    );
  }

  const newPost: Post = {
    id: Date.now(),
    title,
    content,
  };

  posts.push(newPost);

  return NextResponse.json(newPost, { status: 201 });
}
```

Wait, the original didn't specify it returns 201 for POST, but it's good practice. Let me check the original again...

Original POST handler:
```js
export default async function handler(req, res) {
  if (req.method === 'GET') {
    res.status(200).json(posts);
  } else if (req.method === 'POST') {
    const { title, content } = req.body;
    if (!title || !content) {
      res.status(400).json({ error: 'Title and content are required' });
      return;
    }
    const newPost = { id: Date.now(), title, content, createdAt: new Date().toISOString() };
    posts.push(newPost);
    res.status(200).json(newPost);
  } else {
    res.status(405).json({ error: 'Method not allowed' });
  }
}
```

In App Router route handlers, unhandled methods automatically return 405, so I don't need to explicitly handle that.

**`app/api/posts/[id]/route.ts`:**
```ts
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from 'next/server';

interface Post {
  id: number;
  title: string;
  content: string;
  createdAt?: string;
  updatedAt?: string;
}

// Reuse the same in-memory store
const getPosts = () => {
  // In a real app, this would be a database
  const posts: Post[] = [
    { id: 1, title: 'First Post', content: 'This is the first post.' },
    { id: 2, title: 'Second Post', content: 'This is the second post.' },
  ];
  return posts;
};

export async function GET(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const postId = parseInt(id, 10);
  const createdAt = new Date().toISOString();

  const post: Post = { id: postId, title: `Post ${postId}`, content: 'This is a simulated post content.', createdAt };

  return NextResponse.json(post);
}

export async function PUT(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params;
  const body = await request.json();
  const { title, content } = body;

  const updatedPost: Post = {
    id: parseInt(id, 10),
    title: title || `Post ${id}`,
    content: content || 'Updated content.',
    updatedAt: new Date().toISOString(),
  };

  return NextResponse.json(updatedPost);
}

export async function DELETE(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ id: string }> }
) {
  const { id } = await params;

  return NextResponse.json({
    message: `Post ${id} deleted successfully`,
  });
}
```

